{{Infobox venue | name = Amaan Stadium | native_name = {{native phrase|sw|Uwanja wa Amaan}} | former names = | logo_image = | image = Amman Stadium.jpg | caption = | pushpin_map = Tanzania | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Tanzania | address = | location = [[Unguja]], [[Zanzibar City]] | coordinates = {{coord|-6.166003|39.223862|type:landmark_dim:200|display=inline,title}} | type = [[Stadium]] | broke_ground = | built = 1970 | opened = | operator = [[Zanzibar Football Association]] | surface = [[Artificial turf]] | scoreboard = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = 15,000<ref name="stadia">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/africa/countries/tanzania.shtml |title=Stadiums in Tanzania |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher=World Stadiums |accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[KMKM FC]], [[Miembeni S.C.]], [[Mlandege S.C.]]<ref name="stadia"/> | embedded = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | publictransit = }}
'''Amaan Stadium''' (also spelled '''Amani''') is a [[stadium]] in [[Zanzibar]], [[Tanzania]]. The stadium holds 15,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amaan Stadium|url=https://int.soccerway.com/venues/zanzibar/amaan-stadium/|work=Soccerway|publisher=Perform Group|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>
==History== [[File:A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.jpg|thumb|left|A bird's view of Amaan Stadium in Zanzibar.]] The stadium was built with Chinese government aid and opened in 1970.<ref name=alaba>{{cite book|last=Ogunsanwo|first=Alaba|title=China's Policy in Africa, 1958-71|year=1974|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|page=251|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Dn0fbuz4mEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=China's+Policy+in+Africa&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fIOCUsjpB8utkgWd_4HgDQ&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=China's%20Policy%20in%20Africa&f=false}}</ref> This was China's first stadium project in Africa and it marked the beginning of its [[stadium diplomacy]] over the decades.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roadsandkingdoms.com/2014/chinas-stadium-diplomacy-in-africa/ |title=China's Stadium Diplomacy in Africa |last1=Ross |first1=Elliot |last2= |first2= |date=2014 |website= |publisher=Roads & Kingdoms |accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>
The stadium was the location of a ceremony on 5 February 1977, uniting the [[Afro-Shirazi Party]] and the [[Tanganyika African National Union]] into the [[Chama cha Mapinduzi]]. The flags of the respective parties were raised and lowered for the last time with the flag of the Chama cha Mapinduzi then being raised.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Africa|journal=Africa Journal|year=1997|issue=65-70|pages=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=d-pGTsnMNNHTiAKI1qiAAg&ct=result&id=s_DiAAAAMAAJ&dq=Chama+Cha+Amaan+Stadium+Mapinduzi+Tanganyika+Afro-Shirazi+Party+African+National+Union&q=final+time#search_anchor|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Konde|first=Hadji|title=Press freedom in Tanzania|year=1984|publisher=Eastern Africa Publications|location=Arusha [Tanzania]|isbn=9976-2-0029-3|pages=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=d-pGTsnMNNHTiAKI1qiAAg&ct=result&id=Jd-6AAAAIAAJ&dq=Chama+Cha+Amaan+Stadium+Mapinduzi+Tanganyika+Afro-Shirazi+Party+African+National+Union&q=amaan#search_anchor}}</ref> [[Amani Abeid Karume]] was sworn in as president of Zanzibar on 8 November 2000.<ref>{{cite book|title=The East African Journal of Human Rights and Democracy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0vceAQAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=East African Human Rights Institute}}</ref>
The stadium underwent refurbishment again with Chinese assistance, reopening in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=SMZ to protect Amaan Stadium|url=http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/index.php?l=15113|newspaper=Guardian IPP|date=April 1, 2010}}</ref>
The annual [[Revolution Day (Zanzibar)|Revolution Day]] anniversary celebration at the national level is held at the stadium on 12 January.
