{{Infobox stadium | name = John O'Gaunts | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|53.2215|-0.5422|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] }}
'''John O'Gaunts''' was a [[association football|football]] ground in [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]] in [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] from 1884 until 1895.
==History== Located to the south of Lincoln city centre, the John O'Gaunts ground had no spectator facilities and only a dressing room for the players.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p70, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> It took its name from [[John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster]], who owned land in Lincoln.
Lincoln City were elected to the Second Division of [[the Football League]] in 1892, with the first Football League game played at the ground on 1 October 1892 as Lincoln beat [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] 1–0 in front of 2,000 spectators. The highest League attendance at the ground was set on 23 March 1894 when 7,500 watched Lincoln lose 2–0 to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref name=UD/>
At the end of the [[1894–95 Football League|1894–95 season]] the club moved to [[Sincil Bank]], around 300 metres to the south-east. The final League match at John O'Gaunts was played on 13 April 1895, with Lincoln beating [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] 5–2. The ground was later used for housing, and is now the site of Sibthorp Street.<ref name=UD/>
